===Etymology===
Middle English {{term|thoume|lang=enm}}, {{term|thoumbe|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|þuma|þūma|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|þūmōn}} (cf. West Frisian {{term|tomme|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|duim|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Daumen|lang=de}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|tūm-|to grow}} (cf. Welsh {{term|tyfu||to grow|lang=cy}}, Latin {{term|tumere|tumēre|to swell|lang=la}}, Lithuanian {{term|tumėti||to thicken, clot|lang=lt}}, Ancient Greek {{term||týmbos}} 'burial mound', Avestan {{term||tūma}} 'strong', Sanskrit {{term||túmras}} 'strong, thick').

